ST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a lost place called Blackshaw Gap in Rainow (Cheshire) or, possibly, from Blackshaw (Yorkshire), named with Old English <i>blæc</i> ‘black’ + <i>sceaga</i> ‘copse’."],"variants":[{"name":"Blackshear","meanings":["English: variant of   Blackshaw  ."]},{"name":"Blacksher","meanings":["English: variant of   Blackshaw  ."]},{"name":"Blackshire","meanings":["English: variant of   Blackshaw  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":44,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":53,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Blackshaw was born in 1505, in Withington, Cheshire, England as the son of Thomas Blackshaw and Sarah. He married Anne Barkwell about 1529. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He lived in Prestbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom in 1567. He died on 1 June 1565, in Withington, Cheshire, England, at the age of 60, and was buried in